<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>PSYCHOLOGY</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Professor P.C. Lee</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">past president of the Primate Society of Great Britain, a scientific body established for the</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> promotion of research into primate biology, conservation, and captive care, I would like to </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> some comments </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> this enquiry.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> My expertise is not with regard to the numbers of primates held privately, but rather with the fundamental issues of the adequacy of the protection of primate welfare </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for pet primates </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and the appropriateness of the keeping </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of primates as “pets”. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As a result of my </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">39 years of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">experience with non-human primate biology, behaviour and conservation</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> both in the wild and captivity</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[1]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, I can perceive no ethical, husbandry, conservation or historical justifications for continuing to </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allow the keeping of primates as companion animals in the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Should primates be kept in private ownership as “pets”?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">clear </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">distinction </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">needs to be made </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">between a pet as a companion animal to humans </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and those</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> individual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> primates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> being</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> privately</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> housed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or homed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by specialists or experts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the purposes of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">conservation, rehabilitation, protection or promotion of welfare. Private </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">facilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or even individuals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and only those </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which provide the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a high level of care and excellent living conditions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for primates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can be important for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welfare</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of captive individuals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; for example the rescue of abused Spanish beach chimpanzees which were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">originally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">housed in a private sanctuary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> after their rescue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Thus, m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">positive and important examples of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> facilities for rehoming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> primates (often confiscated pets)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> exist</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and these need to be able to continue to provide their important care of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">often highly damaged, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">captive animals.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> however</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> my considered opinion that keeping </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">any</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> primate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, whether by D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">WAA licence or not,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> solely as a companion animal can not be justified on ethical grounds. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The ethics of keeping primates, whether group or singly housed, simply for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">human </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">companionship are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">highly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">questionable. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ethical considerations revolve around </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">morality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> treatment of others</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including non-humans. The justification for applying ethical precepts to non-human primates are based on their demonstrated capacity to suffer, their ancestral kinship with humans, and therefore shared cognitive, emotional and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">perceptual traits between humans and non-human primates</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. In an ethical domain, primate pet owners </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">not have a “moral” justification for keeping these species as companions. However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">although </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on-human primates will remain attra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ctive as companions simply</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> due to these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> perceptual, cognitive and social similarities to humans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uch shared traits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">actually provide the lack</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">justification</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">keeping of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">captive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primates, often in isolation fr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">om same-species companions, in housing that is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inadequate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in terms of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> space or physical complexity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and with limited social or environmental stimulation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. When primates are kept as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">human </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">companions under such conditions, their welfare is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">likely to be substantially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">compromised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, raising further ethical concerns</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Demonstrating compromised welfare is difficult, as long-term pet primates are often genuinely attached to their owners </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(and vice versa) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the absence of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">normative attachments such as with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mothers or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">peers, and we have limited data on the lifespan, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">reprodu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ctive competence, mothering skills, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">health status or wellbeing of pet primates. Welfare concerns can be inferred from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">number of calls to the RSPCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and other animal welfare bodies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> such as the UK primate sanctuaries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with regards to poor welfare o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r mistre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">atment of pet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(and indeed other captive) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primates.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is outside my expertise.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While lacking precise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">quantitative </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">data on the nature</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, extent and diversity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of welfare </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">problems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, it is clear that none but the most specialist keepers (private, public, or co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rporate) are able to house primates in conditions that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">do not jeopardise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">welfare. All primates, even the smallest, have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">very long lifespans of between 16-55 years</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Pet owners would need to ensure appropriate housing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> potentially over the own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er’s own lifespan. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All primates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have a behavioural developmental period that is long by comparison to all mammals, excepting only elephants, dolphins and whales, and humans. Inadequate mothering due to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> enforced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> orphaning and lack of peer experiences d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uring development (associated with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hand-rearing among pets, as well as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capture and the pet trade) produce primates with major behavioural </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and cognitive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disorders in adult life</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All primates live in environments that are rich in stimuli (both positive and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> aversive); such conditions are next to impossible to provide in any captive environment. It is worth noting that many pet owners and captive facilities argue that protecting their animals from adverse conditions is a benefit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of human care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecent research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elk</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, vervet monkeys</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Sykes’s monkeys</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has demonstrated that there are positive genetic, behavioural and even survival consequences of living in challenging environments. Protection from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> natural</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> hazards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> such as predators or conspecific competito</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should not be regarded a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s positive welfare.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Are primates adequat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">ely protected by current legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> obvious that current legislative guidelines </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> allow for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">keeping</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">primates as pets are inadequate;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the majority of species currently kept as pets do not require licences and these are exempted apparently only due to their small body size (marmoset, tamarins and squirrel monkeys)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> rather than on any biological, behavioural or conservation grounds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In fac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> some of the most globally endangered primate species</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are those not requiring any </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">licence or regulatory framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, irrespective of their origins (wild or captive bred)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Issues of compliance with regulatory guidelines are also likely to be problematic as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the resources for enforcement and monitoring are unlikely to be adequate, including CITES (Convention on the Trade in Endangered Species) permits. “Laundering” of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CITES </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Appendix I </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(where all trade is banned) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">species into unregulated trade is commonplace</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The guidelines are also inadequate with regards the detailed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">physical and social requirements that must be met in housing and maintenance for captive primates. In my opinion formal care, husbandry and welfare requirements are lacking except in the most g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eneral sense (cage size, natural light, weaning ages and vague statements about the benefits of social housing) for most UK captive primates despite a number of enquiries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">into conditions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(e.g. Boyd Group Papers)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not withstanding the Nc3R Guidelines which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relate to laboratory primates. Considerable work is required to develop appropriate husbandry guidelines for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> all captive primates</span><a name="_ednref11"></a><a href="#_edn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> “pet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s” require even more consideration given the potential diversity of the “pet environments”. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> straightforward ban wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uld be more effective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and produce better welfare outcomes than merely producing new cage size and enrichment guidelines.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Implementation of a ban</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While a ban on the trade </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in pet primates might have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">financial consequences for the small number of legal an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d legislatively-compliant primate traders, and thus consequences for other exotic and equally threatened species (lizards, snakes, birds etc.) which could replace primates as commodities,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> these might be necessary outcomes only as the ban comes into place. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over time, such consequences will diminish in importance.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Genuine private owners or facilities promoting conservation, rehabilitation and possible reintroduction would need to operate in the future within a clear legislative licencing and inspection fram</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ework, with appropriate and detailed housing and husbandry guidelines – no easy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">task given the diversity of primate species in captivity and their ecological and social needs.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This would have cost implications that would need to be met by the primate owner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The suggestion for a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">complete </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ban on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">future </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">current</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">holders</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">seems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a problematic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> solution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">given </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">problems it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> pose with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deprivation of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> existing owners and their current</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pets of positive affiliative relationships existing between them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a result of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">enforced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">removal, followed by those</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> primates’ placement in some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">undetermined facility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or facilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in the absence of clear long-term fun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ding for such facilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ maintenance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Furthermore such a confiscation facility would have to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adequate space and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">physical and social </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">environments for all these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> probably quite damaged</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prior pets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. A programme of licencing of existing owners (via vets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) and a ban on all future private primate ownership might be a more readily and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">effectively </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implemented. However such a programme would need to include a ban on breedi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> existing licensees so as to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">limit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the options for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">continuation of an unsustainable and unethical practice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font